{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Long-horizon memory is the open problem of giving agents durable, useful recall across tasks that span far more information than any context window can hold. An agent that forgets what it learned an hour ago cannot pursue goals that unfold over days, and no context window is large enough to simply remember everything."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What it is"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Long-horizon memory refers to the mechanisms by which an agent stores experience outside its context window and retrieves the relevant parts when needed. It is the agent analogue of the distinction between a person's working memory (small, transient) and long-term memory (vast, selective). The research problem is not storage — disks are cheap — but "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "selective, faithful retrieval",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "bold"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": surfacing exactly the right past information at the right moment."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "This spans several sub-problems: what to write to memory, how to index it, how to decide what to read back, how to keep it consistent as facts change, and how to forget what is no longer useful. Each is unsolved in the general case, which is why long-horizon memory remains a frontier rather than a settled feature."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why it matters"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The most valuable agent tasks are long-horizon: managing a project, maintaining a codebase, assisting a user over months. These require continuity — remembering decisions, preferences, and prior results — that a stateless model conspicuously lacks. Without memory, every session starts from zero, and the agent cannot accumulate competence."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Simply enlarging the context window does not solve it. Even very long contexts are eventually exceeded, cost grows with length, and models exhibit the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "lost-in-the-middle",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " effect where information buried in a long context is effectively ignored. Memory must be selective precisely because attention is not free and not uniform."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Prerequisites"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Retrieval-augmented generation",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — fetching external records into the prompt on demand."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Embeddings and vector search",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — indexing memories for similarity retrieval."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Context windows",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — their limits, cost, and the lost-in-the-middle effect."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Summarisation",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — compressing history while preserving what matters."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Core concepts"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The memory hierarchy"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Effective agents mirror human memory with tiers: a small working context, a medium-term episodic store of recent events, and a long-term semantic store of durable facts. Information is promoted and demoted between tiers by importance and recency, keeping the expensive context small."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Write, index, read, forget"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A memory system is defined by four operations. Deciding what to write avoids storing noise; indexing determines what can be found; the read policy selects what enters context; and forgetting (or decay) prevents unbounded growth and stale recall. Weakness in any one cripples the whole."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Consistency and staleness"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Facts change: a user's preference updates, a file is edited. A memory that returns an outdated value is worse than no memory. Keeping stored knowledge consistent — updating or invalidating superseded memories — is one of the hardest unsolved parts of the problem."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The lost-in-the-middle effect"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Even when relevant information is in context, models attend most strongly to the beginning and end. Retrieval quality therefore depends not only on finding the right memory but on placing it where the model will actually use it."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Agent memory hierarchy from transient context to consolidated long-term stores"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The retrieval policy and the consolidation process are where the research difficulty concentrates. Storage and embedding are commodity; deciding what deserves to be remembered, and returning a consistent view of it, are not."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How it works"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A retrieval-based memory scores candidate memories against the current query and injects the top few. The relevance component is typically embedding similarity, combined with recency and an importance weight assigned when the memory was written:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockMath",
        "attrs": {
          "latex": "\\text{score}(m, q) = \\lambda_v \\cos\\!\\big(e_m, e_q\\big) + \\lambda_r\\, e^{-\\Delta t / \\tau} + \\lambda_i\\, \\text{imp}(m)"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The decay term "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "e^{-\\Delta t/\\tau}"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " down-weights old memories with a time constant "
          },
          {
            "type": "inlineMath",
            "attrs": {
              "latex": "\\tau"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", so recent context surfaces preferentially while durable, high-importance facts remain reachable regardless of age."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How to implement"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A tiered memory writes salient events, indexes them by embedding, retrieves by the combined score, and consolidates periodically."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import time, math\nfrom dataclasses import dataclass, field\n\n@dataclass\nclass Record:\n    text: str\n    embedding: list\n    importance: float          # 0..1, assigned at write time\n    created: float = field(default_factory=time.time)\n\nclass AgentMemory:\n    def __init__(self, tau_hours=72.0):\n        self.records = []\n        self.tau = tau_hours * 3600\n\n    def write(self, text, embedding, importance):\n        # Skip low-salience noise; only remember what may matter later.\n        if importance < 0.2:\n            return False\n        self.records.append(Record(text, embedding, importance))\n        return True\n\n    def read(self, query_emb, k=5, lv=1.0, lr=0.5, li=0.5):\n        now = time.time()\n        scored = []\n        for r in self.records:\n            rel = cosine(query_emb, r.embedding)\n            rec = math.exp(-(now - r.created) / self.tau)\n            scored.append((lv*rel + lr*rec + li*r.importance, r))\n        scored.sort(key=lambda x: x[0], reverse=True)\n        return [r for _, r in scored[:k]]\n\ndef cosine(a, b):\n    dot = sum(x*y for x, y in zip(a, b))\n    na = math.sqrt(sum(x*x for x in a)); nb = math.sqrt(sum(y*y for y in b))\n    return dot / (na*nb + 1e-9)\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def consolidate(memory, llm, embed, window=50):\n    \"\"\"Summarise and deduplicate recent memories, then supersede the originals.\"\"\"\n    recent = memory.records[-window:]\n    joined = \"\\n\".join(r.text for r in recent)\n    summary = llm(f\"Summarise these events into durable facts, \"\n                  f\"noting any that update earlier ones:\\n{joined}\")\n    for line in summary.split(\"\\n\"):\n        if line.strip():\n            memory.write(line.strip(), embed(line), importance=0.7)\n    # Optionally prune superseded low-importance episodic records here.\n"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Mental model"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Think of the agent as a researcher with a tiny desk and a large filing cabinet. Only a few folders fit on the desk at once, so the researcher's skill is knowing which folders to pull for the question in front of them, and periodically re-filing — merging notes, updating outdated ones, discarding duplicates — so the cabinet stays useful. A bigger desk helps a little, but the real competence is the filing and retrieval discipline, not the desk size."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use it"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use persistent memory when",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " an agent serves the same user or project across many sessions and must retain context."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Use consolidation when",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " raw history grows faster than it can be usefully retrieved, causing noise and staleness."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Prefer a large context window when",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " the entire relevant history genuinely fits and is used within one session."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Add explicit forgetting when",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " stored facts change or expire and stale recall would cause errors."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Avoid heavy memory when",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " tasks are truly independent — persistence then only adds cost and staleness risk."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Real-world example"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Coding assistants that persist across a project are a practical proving ground. They must remember architectural decisions, coding conventions, and past bug fixes so advice stays consistent across sessions. The hard part is consistency: when a convention changes, the memory of the old one must be updated or the assistant will keep recommending the outdated pattern — a concrete instance of the staleness problem."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Performance and scalability"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Retrieval latency and quality both degrade as the store grows, so scaling requires indexing (approximate nearest neighbour) and consolidation to bound the effective size. Cost is dominated by embedding and vector search rather than the language model. The main quality risk at scale is not missing a memory but retrieving many marginally relevant ones that crowd out the few that matter — precision, not recall, becomes the binding constraint."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Tooling and ecosystem"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Vector databases",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — FAISS, Chroma, pgvector, and hosted equivalents index memories at scale."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Memory frameworks",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — libraries such as Mem0 and LangMem package write/read/consolidate policies."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Long-context models",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — extended context windows complement, rather than replace, external memory."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Knowledge graphs",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — structured stores that make consistency and updates more tractable than free text."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Security and reliability"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Memory is persistent state, and persistent state is an attack surface and a privacy liability."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Memory poisoning",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — an adversary who writes false memories biases all future behavior; validate and attribute writes."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Privacy and retention",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — memories may hold sensitive data; enforce retention limits and access control."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Stale-fact errors",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — invalidate superseded memories so the agent never acts on outdated information."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Isolation",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " — separate memory per user or tenant so one context cannot leak into another."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Comparison with alternatives"
